>[Question]
>Hi, i was wondering if it is possible to multiply two DIFFERENT 
>irrational numbers and get a rational number
>
>[Difficulty]
>Please, help, i have no idea how to solve this
>
>[Thoughts]
>I know that if you multiply the square root of 2 by the square root 
>of 2, you get the square of 4, which is 2. so the square root of 2 is 
>irrational but when you multiply it by itself, the answer would be 2 
>which is rational, now do you think it is possible to multipy two 
>irrational numbers that are different and still get a rational 
>number? thanks

Hi Mike,

Here's a hint:  Given two numbers, a and b, 

  (a + b)(a - b) = a^2 - b^2

Note that (a+b) and (a-b) are two different numbers...

Does that help? 

